The barleycorn unit of measure existed prior to Roman based measurement systems of post-1066 as a basic Anglo Saxon unit, simply the length of a corn of barley. After 1066, the unit was standardized to about 1/3 inch, and during the reign of Edward I, it was decreed that three grains of dry, round barley make an inch, twelve inches make a foot; three feet make an ulna (yard). So, simply stated, a barleycorn is 1/3 inch.